        <h2>Design Basics</h2>

        <ul>

        <li><b>Proper Labels</b>
        <p>Most importantly, <b>buttons and links should demonstrate the verbal tone for the entire project</b>. Labels like "click here", "confirm" or "okay" should never be used as their ambiguity will cause confusion for the User. Instead, ensure that the text used for every button is relevant to its context and conveys what will actually be done. Try to maintain a common vocabulary and avoid switching between terms like "cancel" and "exit" without conveying a distinction between the two's purpose or function. </p>
        </li>

        <li><b>Flexible Design</b>
        <p>A button's design should be simple and resilient. Pairing a button label with an icon reinforces meaning and quickens recognition. When adding an element, even a simple icon, a button layout shouldn't break down.</p>
        </li>

        <li><b>One Primary Button Only</b>
        <p>A button should be used to draw the User's attention to a singular objective: continuing or completing a task. Because of this, it's important to limit the amount of primary buttons that display on a single page.</p>
        </li>

        <li><b>Distinguishable States</b>
        <p>Every interactive element should have multiple "states" in which it can exist. For buttons, there are six states: default, focus, press, hover, disabled, and progress. Links share all the same states except for "progress".</p>
        </li>

        <li><b>Contextual Color</b>
        <p>Additionally, consider if the action that is being performed is <span class="text-success">constructive</span>, <span class="text-danger">destructive</span>, or <span class="text-secondary">neither</span>. Particular styling should be put in place for each of these situations. Commonly, destructive actions are colored red, while constructive actions are colored green. Either should also be accompanied by an icon to help demonstrate exactly what kind of action is taking place as well as assisting any colorblind users to distinguish what kind of action is taking place. </p>
        </li>

        <li><b>No Grey Buttons</b>
        <p>No one yearns for gray buttons. This color should solely be reserved for disabled buttons. Secondary buttons should be either outlined or styled in a secondary color.</p>
        </li>

        </ul>

